<div>		



<span class="section_title">HOME THEATER MARKET DISPLAYS LATEST SIGHTS AND SOUNDS AT THE 2007 INTERNATIONAL CES</span>

	<br><br>
	<span class="subhead">CES Conferences and TechZones to Cover Expanding Home Theater Market</span>

<br><br>		
<strong><i>Arlington, Virginia&nbsp;-&nbsp;12/21/2006</i></strong>
<br><br>
The sights and sounds of home theater technologies will once again 

be a featured attraction at the 2007 International CES<sup>&#174</sup>, the world's largest consumer technology 

tradeshow.  CES returns to Las Vegas, January 8-11, 2007 for its 40<sup>th</sup> anniversary celebration.
<p>
      "The latest advancements in audio and video technologies are driving the home theater market to new heights 

and CES is the place to see the latest and greatest products in this space," said Karen Chupka, senior vice 

president of events and conferences for the Consumer Electronics Association (CEA<sup>&#174</sup>), the producer of 

the International CES.  "High-definition televisions and high-performance audio systems are in high demand and 

together are a powerful home theater combination."
<p>
	Key home theater exhibitors at the 2007 International CES include: Dolby Laboratories Inc., DTS, Earthquake 

Sound Corp., Kimber Kable, Klipsch/Jamo/Mirage/Energy, Meridian, Monster, Optoma Technology, Polk Audio, 

Runco/Vidikron, Thomson, THX Ltd., TTE and Westinghouse Digital Electronics.
<p>
	Home theater exhibitors can be found at two locations at the 2007 International CES. Home theater exhibits 

will be featured in the South Hall of the Las Vegas Convention Center (LVCC) and high-performance audio and home 

theater exhibitors will be showcased at CES' Sands Expo and Convention Center/The Venetian.  
<p>
      The 2007 International CES also will house more than 175 conference and SuperSessions, enabling attendees to 

hear from top industry professionals on key technologies and trends, including the latest emerging developments in 

the home theater industry.  Home theater-specific conference sessions include:  <i>The New Face of TV</i>, 

<i>Blu-Ray vs. HD-DVD: And the Winner Is...</i>, <i>TV Technology Showdown</i> and <i>IPTV: Television over the 

Internet</i>.
<p>
      For CES attendees interested in learning the latest trends in high-performance audio and home theater, 

<i>Audio Innovators</i>, <i>Last Gadget Standing</i>, <i>Technology with Looks that Kill: But What About 

Performance?</i> and <i>Creating an Audio Step-up Market in the Age of the IPod</i> are the conferences to attend.  
<p>            
      The 2007 International CES features more than 20 market-specific TechZones, including the latest developments 

in the home theater category. Related TechZones for home theater technology include the Connected Home Entertainment 

TechZone, which focuses on the benefits of whole-house audio and video technology, the HD-DVD Promotion Group 

TechZone, featuring the latest in HD-DVD technology and the NextGen Home Experience TechZone, showcasing the ideal 

home theater system.
<p>
      For more news on CES before, during and after the show, visit <a 

href="http://www.CESweb.org">http://www.CESweb.org</a>, the interactive source for CES information.
<p>
<b>ABOUT CEA:</b><br>
The Consumer Electronics Association (CEA) is the preeminent trade association promoting growth in the consumer 

technology industry through technology policy, events, research, promotion and the fostering of business and 

strategic relationships.  CEA represents more than 2,100 corporate members involved in the design, development, 

manufacturing, distribution and integration of audio, video, mobile electronics, wireless and landline 

communications, information technology, home networking, multimedia and accessory products, as well as related 

services that are sold through consumer channels. Combined, CEA's members account for more than $125 billion in 

annual sales.  CEA's resources are available online at <a href="http://www.CE.org">www.CE.org</a>, the definitive 

source for information about the consumer electronics industry. CEA also sponsors and manages the International CES 

- Defining Tomorrow's Technology.  All profits from CES are reinvested into industry services, including technical 

training and education, industry promotion, engineering standards development, market research and legislative 

advocacy.
<br><br>
